{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642553"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:41:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17952"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17952"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.92,0,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73008"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17952"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7244"},{"type":"tags","id":"7294"},{"type":"tags","id":"11250"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24848"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73008"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following functions is the temporomandibular joint primarily involved in?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smelling","Mastication","Hearing","Swallowing","Vision"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe temporomandibular joint (TMJ) is a hinge joint that connects the jawbone to the skull. It plays a critical role in \u003Cstrong\u003Emastication\u003C/strong\u003E, which involves the movement of the jaw necessary for chewing food. The TMJ allows for the opening, closing, and side-to-side movements of the jaw, which are essential for grinding and breaking down food.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the TMJ is involved in other oral functions such as speech, it is not directly involved in \u003Cstrong\u003Ehearing\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Evision\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eswallowing\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003Esmelling\u003C/strong\u003E. These functions are associated with different anatomical structures and systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDysfunction of the TMJ can lead to symptoms such as pain, clicking, and difficulty in chewing, as seen in this patient. Management may include lifestyle modifications, physical therapy, or in some cases, surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The temporomandibular joint (TMJ) plays a crucial role in mastication, allowing for the movement of the jaw necessary for chewing.","The TMJ is a complex joint that also facilitates speech and other oral functions.","Dysfunction of the TMJ can lead to pain, difficulty in chewing, and other complications."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17952"}